112
00:07:12,297 --> 00:07:14,493
Yes, we should.
Alan was our friend.

113
00:07:14,493 --> 00:07:17,166
What can I say to her?
I don't have any words.

114
00:07:17,166 --> 00:07:19,211
You will.
I know it.

115
00:07:19,211 --> 00:07:21,045
You always do.

116
00:07:34,496 --> 00:07:37,976
Diane, we are so sorry.

117
00:07:38,891 --> 00:07:40,863
How can you come here?

118
00:07:40,863 --> 00:07:43,442
We loved Alan.

119
00:07:43,865 --> 00:07:46,636
You killed him.

120
00:07:46,636 --> 00:07:49,780
He didn't, Diane.
It was a horrible accident.

121
00:07:49,780 --> 00:07:52,612
I've contacted a lawyer.

122
00:07:52,612 --> 00:07:54,596
Diane. No.

123
00:07:54,596 --> 00:07:57,607
I want to see you 
lose something too.

124
00:07:57,607 --> 00:07:59,672
I'm sorry for loss.

125
00:07:59,672 --> 00:08:02,578
And you'll be sorry 
for your losses.

126
00:08:16,474 --> 00:08:18,491
Sounds like a threat.

127
00:08:18,491 --> 00:08:20,241
She was in shock.

128
00:08:20,241 --> 00:08:21,613
Grieving.

129
00:08:21,613 --> 00:08:24,385
That's when people do things
they couldn't normally stomach.

130
00:08:24,385 --> 00:08:27,863
My wife was killed by a blond
and a shaggy man.

131
00:08:27,863 --> 00:08:30,051
Diane had brown hair.

132
00:08:30,051 --> 00:08:33,453
Still, no one had 
motive like she did.

133
00:08:34,017 --> 00:08:36,835
It's not possible.

134
00:08:36,835 --> 00:08:39,902
We weren't those kind of people.

135
00:08:40,025 --> 00:08:42,111
No one ever is.

136
00:08:47,802 --> 00:08:50,378
Diane Moore?

137
00:08:50,795 --> 00:08:53,461
- Do I know you?
- I'm Detective Valens, Homicide.

138
00:08:53,461 --> 00:08:55,189
Nice ride.

139
00:08:56,069 --> 00:08:57,745
Well, it gets me there.

140
00:08:57,745 --> 00:09:01,859
It's about Lindsay Chase.

141
00:09:04,025 --> 00:09:07,178
- What about Lindsay?
- We're looking at her murder again.

142
00:09:07,178 --> 00:09:10,145
Poor Steven's been paying for that
for twenty years.

143
00:09:10,145 --> 00:09:11,500
Poor Steven?

144
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:13,747
He was a good friend at one time.

145
00:09:13,747 --> 00:09:16,412
Are you singing a different tune
than you did in '82?

146
00:09:16,412 --> 00:09:17,847
The way I heard it,

147
00:09:17,847 --> 00:09:20,696
you gave it to Steven and Lindsay 
pretty good at your husband's funeral.

148
00:09:20,696 --> 00:09:22,214
Sent them away.

149
00:09:22,214 --> 00:09:28,357
I was out of my head
when I lost Alan.

150
00:09:28,357 --> 00:09:30,415
I couldn't see pass the pain.

151
00:09:30,415 --> 00:09:33,799
- Yeah?
- I wanted their world to crumble.

152
00:09:34,690 --> 00:09:37,180
- Like mine had.
- And that's why the lawsuit.

153
00:09:37,180 --> 00:09:39,627
And it broke them.

154
00:09:39,812 --> 00:09:44,020
He couldn't practice, pay 
the mortgage. They were a cash poor.

155
00:09:44,020 --> 00:09:45,980
Plus, Chase got real depressed.

156
00:09:45,980 --> 00:09:49,171
It was a horror show.

157
00:09:49,171 --> 00:09:51,981
And I couldn't get enough of it.

158
00:10:04,193 --> 00:10:05,860
Lindsay, hi.

159
00:10:05,860 --> 00:10:07,975
- D'you need a color?
- No.

160
00:10:07,975 --> 00:10:10,510
Well, yeah.
But that's not why I'm here.

161
00:10:10,510 --> 00:10:13,518
I'm looking for employment.

162
00:10:14,623 --> 00:10:17,224
I don't have professional experience,
but I'm good with hair and nails.

163
00:10:17,224 --> 00:10:20,474
Kitty, I've got aerobics in 20 minutes.

164
00:10:20,474 --> 00:10:21,893
2 secs, Diane.

165
00:10:21,893 --> 00:10:25,426
No, now.
I'm the one paying you.

166
00:10:29,481 --> 00:10:32,425
Look, all I've got is hair
sweeping stuff.

167
00:10:32,425 --> 00:10:35,870
It's a minimum wage and it's
your friends's hair.

168
00:10:35,870 --> 00:10:38,986
They're not my friends anymore.
So I don't mind.

169
00:10:38,986 --> 00:10:42,861
I just need to make enough
for groceries till Steven gets better.

170
00:10:43,900 --> 00:10:45,171
Sure.

171
00:10:45,171 --> 00:10:47,481
It'll be great, Linds.
Welcome.

172
00:10:54,355 --> 00:10:57,628
I was so distraught...

173
00:10:57,628 --> 00:11:00,867
I actually enjoyed 
watching her suffer.

174
00:11:00,924 --> 00:11:06,267
It wasn't until later I thought
maybe it was me.

175
00:11:06,526 --> 00:11:10,024
- You what?
- Who caused her death.

176
00:11:10,070 --> 00:11:13,696
Maybe the lawsuit drove 
Steven over the edge,

177
00:11:13,696 --> 00:11:16,520
made him kill her.

178
00:11:19,636 --> 00:11:22,188
Anything on our dead blond junkie?

179
00:11:22,188 --> 00:11:24,339
Looked into her glorious past.

180
00:11:24,339 --> 00:11:26,569
Few jobs, stint in rehab, usual story.

181
00:11:26,569 --> 00:11:28,211
No connect to the Chases?

182
00:11:28,211 --> 00:11:29,652
Scotty have better luck?

183
00:11:29,652 --> 00:11:32,837
Well, Lindsay Chase may have taken 
a low rent job a few months before she died.

184
00:11:32,837 --> 00:11:34,340
Will's running that down.

185
00:11:34,340 --> 00:11:35,302
Struck out.

186
00:11:35,302 --> 00:11:40,166
IRS has no record of her working
at the Patrick Brea Salon or anywhere else.

187
00:11:40,166 --> 00:11:41,673
What's it Salon?

188
00:11:41,673 --> 00:11:44,368
Brea.
B.R.E.A.

189
00:11:45,846 --> 00:11:50,824
That was Melanie Castle's 
employer, January to August, '82.

190
00:11:50,824 --> 00:11:53,008
That's the same time Lindsay
was killed.

191
00:11:53,008 --> 00:11:56,785
So our blond and Lindsay Chase
were co-workers.

192
00:12:11,874 --> 00:12:14,235
Kitty Shaw?

193
00:12:15,385 --> 00:12:17,385
Katarine.

194
00:12:17,385 --> 00:12:20,158
I figured I'd upgrade the name
and the rest of my life would follow.

195
00:12:20,158 --> 00:12:22,151
Tada.

196
00:12:22,608 --> 00:12:26,063
Detectives Rush and Jeffries.
Homicide.

197
00:12:26,719 --> 00:12:29,939
We're wondering if you remember
Lindsay Chase.

198
00:12:29,939 --> 00:12:32,847
Of course.
She was my friend.

199
00:12:32,847 --> 00:12:34,289
Why don't we...

200
00:12:36,304 --> 00:12:38,954
What about Melanie Castle?

201
00:12:39,067 --> 00:12:43,155
We worked together like,
million years ago.

202
00:12:43,155 --> 00:12:45,644
Yikes, why?

203
00:12:47,522 --> 00:12:49,526
Melanie died two days ago.

204
00:12:49,526 --> 00:12:52,823
- Heroine overdose.
- Oh god, no.

205
00:12:53,115 --> 00:12:54,602
What does that have to do
with Lindsay?

206
00:12:54,602 --> 00:12:56,421
We're taking another look
at her murder.

207
00:12:56,421 --> 00:12:57,979
I thought her husband killed her.

208
00:12:57,979 --> 00:13:01,406
We heard she might have worked 
for you back at Patrick Brea Salon.

209
00:13:01,406 --> 00:13:03,685
That's what we hear, 
but there's no record of it.

210
00:13:03,685 --> 00:13:05,356
We paid her under the table.

211
00:13:05,356 --> 00:13:07,599
Paid most of the sweepers
under table.

212
00:13:07,599 --> 00:13:09,369
- Like Melanie?
- Yeah.

213
00:13:09,369 --> 00:13:12,125
Now, those two, that,

214
00:13:12,125 --> 00:13:13,872
that was a culture clash.

215
00:13:13,872 --> 00:13:16,738
And Melanie didn't appreciate
the extra help with the broom?

216
00:13:16,738 --> 00:13:22,650
I don't think Melanie thought of Lindsay 
as a helpful presence in her life.

217
00:13:22,650 --> 00:13:24,288
No.

218
00:13:37,789 --> 00:13:39,373
Feel better?

219
00:13:39,373 --> 00:13:42,180
I'm sorry.
You probably had plans.

220
00:13:42,180 --> 00:13:44,409
- I didn't mean to cry at work.
- Hey.

221
00:13:44,409 --> 00:13:48,244
I'd cry too if my super-hunk hubby
was depressed in bed all day.

222
00:13:48,244 --> 00:13:51,954
Plus, I thought 8 hours would
add up to more than this.

223
00:13:52,676 --> 00:13:54,450
Steven's gonna pull through.

224
00:13:54,450 --> 00:13:57,219
He's got a million reasons
to get out of bed.

225
00:13:57,309 --> 00:13:59,870
You, is one.

226
00:14:01,216 --> 00:14:04,484
- We're talking, okay?
- Tell Timmy.

227
00:14:04,484 --> 00:14:06,760
I wanted to sit at the bar.

228
00:14:06,760 --> 00:14:08,368
Is this a girl thing?

229
00:14:08,368 --> 00:14:10,249
No, it's fine.

230
00:14:11,342 --> 00:14:13,040
Hi.

231
00:14:14,795 --> 00:14:16,404
Timmy, this is Lindsay.

232
00:14:16,404 --> 00:14:18,493
Yeah, I saw you before.

233
00:14:18,737 --> 00:14:20,910
You're not driving 
the beemer anymore.

234
00:14:22,028 --> 00:14:24,230
